    <text>
    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Lake Point Hotel, Great Salt Lake | Tooele Valley, Utah Ter.</placeName>
                    <date>March 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1879.</date>
                    <seg type="supplemental">Mr. Charles Darwin</seg>
                    <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>While reading your work on the Origin of Species I came to that part, in which you treat of inherited effects and thinking that the following curious fact might be of some little interest to you I have taken the liberty of writing to you.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Several years ago a gentleman in Washington through sickness, became completely bald, after his recovery he married and has now five children, three sons and two daughters. At a corresponding age the three sons successively became as bald as their father while the daughters do not show the slightest signs of loosing their hair.</p>
<p>Do you not think this an astonishingly good example of inherited effects?</p>
<p>Resp’t’f’ly Yrs. | C.H. Browning</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6019.xml"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 6th ed.</ref>, pp. 108–9, CD had noted that the evidence that accidental mutilations could be inherited was not decisive. Browning has not been identified.</note>
        </div>   
       
    </body>
